Wash and dry all produce. Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Place @bacon{4%ounce} in a large pan
over medium-high heat. Cook to desired doneness, ~{3-6%minutes} per side. Transfer to a
#paper-towel-lined plate{}, keeping grease in pan. Once bacon is cool, chop into
bite-sized pieces.

Meanwhile, halve, peel, and thinly slice @red onion{1}. Add onion and @sugar{pinch} to pan
used for bacon. Cook, tossing, until onion is a deep golden brown, ~{10-12%minutes}.
Stir in @balsamic vinegar{1%tsp} (we'll be using the rest later) and continue cooking until
liquid has evaporated, about ~{3%minutes} longer.

Halve, core, and slice @Granny Smith apple{1}. Heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{1%tbsp} in
another large pan over medium-high heat. Add apple slices in a single layer. Cook, tossing
occasionally, until softened, ~{5-7%minutes}.

While onion and apple cook, place @flatbreads{2} on a #baking sheet{}. Toast in oven until
very lightly toasted, ~{5-7%minutes}. In a #small bowl{}, combine @ricotta cheese{4%ounce},
a drizzle of @olive oil{}, and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Spread ricotta mixture over flatbreads. Evenly scatter onion, apple, and bacon over each.

> TIP: Don't overload the flatbreads; you may have some toppings left over.

Return baking sheet to oven and bake until toppings are toasty and lightly crisped,
~{5-7%minutes}.

Drizzle flatbreads with @honey{1/2%ounce} and remaining @balsamic vinegar{1%tablespoon}.
Cut into slices and serve.